body:
MAILE. In old English law. A _ kind
of ancient money, or silver half-pence; a
small rent. ;

MAISON DE DIEU. Fr. A hospital;
an almshouse; a monastery. St. 39 Eliz. c.
5. Literally, “house of God.”

MARQUIS, or MARQUESS. In English
law. One of the second order of nobility;
next in order to a duke.

MERANNUM.
Wood for building.


In old records. Timbers;

MICHERY.
cheating.


In old English law. Theft;

MISCEGENATION. Mixture of races;
marriage between persons of different races;
as between a white person and a negro.

MUEBLES. In Spanish law. Movables;
all sorts of personal property. White, New
Recop. b. 1, tit. 3, c. 1, § 2.

MUTA-CANUM. A kennel of hounds;
one of the mortuaries to which the crown
was entitled at a bishop’s or abbot’s decease. 2 Bl. Comm. 426.
